import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the dataset
df = pd.read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/owid/energy-data/master/owid-energy-data.csv")

# Separate countries and individual entities
countries_list = df[~df['iso_code'].isna() == True ]['country'].unique().tolist()

# Identify entities that are regions/groupings rather than individual countries
region_keywords = ['World', '(EI)', 'OECD', 'Union', 'income countries', 'Asia Pacific', 'CIS', 'Middle East', 'Central America']
regional_entities = [country for country in df['country'].unique() if any(keyword in str(country) for keyword in region_keywords)]

# Create dataframes for countries and regions
df_regions = df[df['country'].isin(regional_entities)]
df_countries = df[~df['country'].isin(regional_entities)]

# Filter years to start from 2000
df = df[df['year']>=2000]
df_regions = df_regions[df_regions['year']>=2000]
df_countries = df_countries[df_countries['year']>=2000]

# Filter years to start from 2000
df = df[df['year']>=2000]
df_regions = df_regions[df_regions['year']>=2000]

# Find the latest year with complete data for all metrics
required_columns = ['population', 'primary_energy_consumption', 'energy_per_gdp', 
                    'gdp', 'energy_per_capita']
latest_years = {}

for col in required_columns:
    # Get the years where data exists for this column
    years_with_data = df[df[col].notna()]['year'].unique()
    if len(years_with_data) > 0:
        latest_years[col] = int(max(years_with_data))

# Find the most recent year that has data for all required columns
LATEST_YEAR = min(latest_years.values())
print(f"Latest year with complete data: {LATEST_YEAR}")
print(f"Latest available year per metric: {latest_years}")

# Percentage of total per year calculation
df['population_pct'] = df['population'] / df.groupby('year')['population'].transform('sum')*100
df['primary_energy_consumption_pct'] = df['primary_energy_consumption'] / df.groupby('year')['primary_energy_consumption'].transform('sum')*100
df['gdp_pct'] = df['gdp'] / df.groupby('year')['gdp'].transform('sum')*100

df_regions['population_pct'] = df_regions['population'] / df_regions.groupby('year')['population'].transform('sum')*100
df_regions['primary_energy_consumption_pct'] = df_regions['primary_energy_consumption'] / df_regions.groupby('year')['primary_energy_consumption'].transform('sum')*100
df_regions['gdp_pct'] = df_regions['gdp'] / df_regions.groupby('year')['gdp'].transform('sum')*100

# Create top 10 lists using the latest year with complete data
top_10_population_list = df_countries[df_countries['year']==LATEST_YEAR].nlargest(10, 'population')['country'].to_list()
top_10_energy_intensity_list = df_countries[df_countries['year']==LATEST_YEAR].nlargest(10, 'energy_per_gdp')['country'].to_list()
bottom_10_energy_intensity_list = df_countries[df_countries['year']==LATEST_YEAR].nsmallest(10, 'energy_per_gdp')['country'].to_list()
top_10_gdp_list = df_countries[df_countries['year']==LATEST_YEAR].nlargest(10, 'gdp')['country'].to_list()
top_10_energy_consumption_list = df_countries[df_countries['year']==LATEST_YEAR].nlargest(10, 'primary_energy_consumption')['country'].to_list()

# Verify Saudi Arabia has data
if 'Saudi Arabia' in df_countries['country'].unique():
    saudi_data = df_countries[df_countries['country'] == 'Saudi Arabia']
    has_saudi_data = saudi_data['energy_per_gdp'].notna().any()
    print(f"Saudi Arabia data available: {has_saudi_data}")
    if has_saudi_data:
        print(f"Saudi Arabia energy intensity in {LATEST_YEAR}: {saudi_data[saudi_data['year']==LATEST_YEAR]['energy_per_gdp'].values}")
else:
    print("Saudi Arabia not found in dataset")

# Create a function for styling tables
def style_table(table, highlight_rows=[0, -1]):
    """Apply consistent styling to tables"""
    table.auto_set_font_size(False)
    table.set_fontsize(10)
    table.scale(1, 2)
    
    # Apply custom coloring
    for (row, col), cell in table.get_celld().items():
        if row in highlight_rows:
            cell.set_text_props(fontproperties=FontProperties(weight='bold'), color='white')
            cell.set_facecolor('#3949ab')
        elif row % 2 == 0:
            cell.set_facecolor('#f5f5f5')
        else:
            cell.set_facecolor('#e1e1e1')
            
        # Add borders
        cell.set_edgecolor('#333333')

# Prepare data for countries with highest energy intensity
df_high_energy = df_countries.query(f'(year in [{LATEST_YEAR}])').nlargest(10, 'energy_per_gdp').sort_values(by=['energy_per_gdp'], ascending=False)
df_high_energy.loc['Total',:] = df_high_energy.sum(axis=0)
df_high_energy.loc[df_high_energy.index[-1], 'country'] = 'Average'
df_high_energy.loc[df_high_energy.index[-1], 'energy_per_gdp'] = df_high_energy['energy_per_gdp'].mean()
df_high_energy = df_high_energy.round(2)

# Create figure with enhanced styling
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, figsize=(15, 12), gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': [3, 1]})
fig.suptitle(f'Energy Intensity (Energy per GDP) in Highest Countries (2000-{LATEST_YEAR})', 
             fontweight='bold', fontsize=18, y=0.98)

# Adding a subtle background color
fig.patch.set_facecolor('#f8f9fa')

# Plot with improved styling
for i, entity in enumerate(top_10_energy_intensity_list):
    color = country_colors.get(entity, sns.color_palette()[i % 10])
    data = df[df['country']==entity]
    ax1.plot(data['year'], data['energy_per_gdp'], 
             label=entity, linewidth=2.5, color=color,
             marker='o', markevery=10, markersize=5)

# Add reference lines and highlights
ax1.axvspan(LATEST_YEAR-12, LATEST_YEAR, color='#f5f5f5', alpha=0.3)

# Add world average for comparison
world_avg_by_year = df.groupby('year')['energy_per_gdp'].mean()
ax1.plot(world_avg_by_year.index, world_avg_by_year.values, 
         label='Global Average', linewidth=3, 
         linestyle='--', color='black')

# Improve axis formatting and labels
ax1.set_ylabel('Energy Intensity (kWh per $)', fontweight='bold')
ax1.set_xlabel('Year', fontweight='bold')
ax1.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Enhance legend with better positioning and style
legend = ax1.legend(loc="upper right", frameon=True, fancybox=True, 
                   shadow=True, fontsize=10, title="Countries")
legend.get_title().set_fontweight('bold')

# Create improved table
column_labels = [
    'Country', 
    'Energy per GDP (kWh/$)', 
    'Energy Consumption (TWh)', 
    'GDP (int-$ 2011)'
]

the_table = ax2.table(
    cellText=df_high_energy[['country','energy_per_gdp','primary_energy_consumption','gdp']].values, 
    colLabels=column_labels,
    cellLoc='center', 
    loc='center'
)
style_table(the_table)

ax2.axis('off')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.92)

# Improve visual hierarchy
for spine in ax1.spines.values():
    spine.set_linewidth(1.5)
    
# Add a title for the table section
plt.figtext(0.5, 0.48, f'Highest Energy Intensity Countries Data for {LATEST_YEAR}', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', ha='center')

# Add a footnote
plt.figtext(0.5, 0.01, 'Data source: Our World in Data (OWID)', 
           ha='center', fontsize=8, style='italic')

# Get data for latest year
df_latest = df_countries[df_countries['year'] == LATEST_YEAR]

# Filter for countries with significant GDP and good data quality (top 30)
significant_countries = df_latest.dropna(subset=['energy_per_gdp']).nlargest(30, 'gdp')

# Remove countries with missing energy intensity data
significant_countries = significant_countries[significant_countries['energy_per_gdp'].notna()]
print(f"Number of major economies with complete data: {len(significant_countries)}")

# Sort by energy intensity
significant_countries = significant_countries.sort_values('energy_per_gdp')

# Create figure
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))

# Create bar chart with only countries that have data
bars = plt.barh(significant_countries['country'], significant_countries['energy_per_gdp'])

# Add title with actual year used in analysis
plt.title(f'Energy Intensity in Major Economies ({LATEST_YEAR})', 
          fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)

# Color bars according to intensity
norm = plt.Normalize(significant_countries['energy_per_gdp'].min(), 
                     significant_countries['energy_per_gdp'].max())
colors = plt.cm.YlOrRd(norm(significant_countries['energy_per_gdp']))

for bar, color in zip(bars, colors):
    bar.set_color(color)

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('Energy Intensity (kWh per $)', fontweight='bold')
plt.title(f'Energy Intensity in Major Economies ({LATEST_YEAR})', 
          fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)

# Add grid
plt.grid(axis='x', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Add world average line
world_avg = df_latest['energy_per_gdp'].mean()
plt.axvline(x=world_avg, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=2)
plt.text(world_avg, -1, f'Global Average: {world_avg:.2f}', 
        ha='center', va='top', fontweight='bold', backgroundcolor='#f8f9fa')

# Adjust layout
plt.tight_layout()

# Add colorbar
fig, ax = plt.gcf(), plt.gca()  # Get current figure and axes
sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=plt.cm.YlOrRd, norm=norm)
sm.set_array([])
cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, ax=ax)  # Pass the current axes to fix the colorbar issue
cbar.set_label('Energy Intensity', fontweight='bold')

# Add annotations for notable countries
for i, country in enumerate(significant_countries['country']):
    intensity = significant_countries.iloc[i]['energy_per_gdp']
    if country in ['China', 'United States', 'India', 'Russia', 'France', 'Brazil', 'United Kingdom', 'Japan', 'Germany']:
        plt.text(intensity + 0.1, i, f'{intensity:.2f}', va='center', fontweight='bold')

# Add a footnote
plt.figtext(0.5, 0.01, 'Data source: Our World in Data (OWID)', 
           ha='center', fontsize=8, style='italic')

# Create scatter plot showing energy intensity vs GDP
# Get data for latest year
df_latest = df[df['year'] == LATEST_YEAR]

# Create figure
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))

# Create scatter plot with size based on total energy consumption
scatter = plt.scatter(df_latest['gdp'], 
                     df_latest['energy_per_gdp'],
                     s=df_latest['primary_energy_consumption']/50,  # Size based on energy consumption
                     alpha=0.7,
                     c=df_latest['energy_per_capita'],  # Color based on energy per capita
                     cmap='viridis')

# Add labels for key countries
countries_to_label = []
# Top 15 GDP
countries_to_label.extend(df_latest.nlargest(15, 'gdp')['country'].tolist())
# Top 5 highest energy intensity
countries_to_label.extend(df_latest.nlargest(5, 'energy_per_gdp')['country'].tolist())
# Top 5 lowest energy intensity
countries_to_label.extend(df_latest.nsmallest(5, 'energy_per_gdp')['country'].tolist())

# Remove duplicates
countries_to_label = list(set(countries_to_label))

for country in countries_to_label:
    country_data = df_latest[df_latest['country'] == country]
    if not country_data.empty:
        x = country_data['gdp'].values[0]
        y = country_data['energy_per_gdp'].values[0]
        plt.annotate(country, (x, y), fontsize=9, fontweight='bold',
                    xytext=(5, 5), textcoords='offset points')

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('GDP (int-$ 2011)', fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Energy Intensity (kWh per $)', fontweight='bold')
plt.title(f'Energy Intensity vs GDP ({LATEST_YEAR})', 
          fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)

# Add grid
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Use log scale for x-axis due to wide range
plt.xscale('log')

# Add reference lines
world_avg_intensity = df_latest['energy_per_gdp'].mean()
plt.axhline(y=world_avg_intensity, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=1.5)
plt.text(plt.xlim()[0]*1.1, world_avg_intensity, f'Global Average: {world_avg_intensity:.2f}', 
        va='center', fontweight='bold', backgroundcolor='#f8f9fa')

# Add colorbar
fig, ax = plt.gcf(), plt.gca()  # Get current figure and axes
norm = plt.Normalize(df_latest['energy_per_capita'].min(), df_latest['energy_per_capita'].max())
sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap='viridis', norm=norm)
sm.set_array([])
cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, ax=ax)  # Pass the current axes to fix the colorbar issue
cbar.set_label('Energy per Capita (kWh)', fontweight='bold')

# Add size legend
sizes = [5000, 20000, 40000]  # Energy consumption in TWh
for size in sizes:
    plt.scatter([], [], s=size/50, c='gray', alpha=0.5, label=f'{size} TWh')

plt.legend(title='Energy Consumption', loc='upper right', frameon=True, 
          fancybox=True, shadow=True)

# Add explanatory annotations
plt.annotate('Developed Economies\nLow Energy Intensity', 
            xy=(df_latest['gdp'].max()*0.1, world_avg_intensity*0.5),
            xytext=(df_latest['gdp'].max()*0.1, world_avg_intensity*0.5),
            fontsize=12, fontweight='bold', color='green', ha='center')

plt.annotate('Energy-Intensive\nEconomies', 
            xy=(df_latest['gdp'].max()*0.1, world_avg_intensity*2),
            xytext=(df_latest['gdp'].max()*0.1, world_avg_intensity*2),
            fontsize=12, fontweight='bold', color='darkred', ha='center')

# Add a footnote
plt.figtext(0.5, 0.01, 'Data source: Our World in Data (OWID)', 
           ha='center', fontsize=8, style='italic')

# Create a visualization showing historical trends for key countries
# Select diverse major economies with good data availability
major_economies = ['China', 'United States', 'India', 'Russia', 'Germany', 
                  'France', 'Brazil', 'Japan', 'Canada', 'United Kingdom', 
                  'South Korea', 'Indonesia', 'Australia']

# Verify data coverage and only include countries with good coverage
selected_countries = []
for country in major_economies:
    country_data = df_countries[df_countries['country'] == country]
    years_with_data = country_data[country_data['energy_per_gdp'].notna()]['year'].unique()
    # Use explicit START_YEAR and END_YEAR values instead of variables
    coverage = len(years_with_data) / (2019 - 2000 + 1)
    
    if coverage >= 0.7:  # At least 70% of years have data
        selected_countries.append(country)
        print(f"{country}: {len(years_with_data)} years of data ({coverage:.0%} coverage)")
    else:
        print(f"Excluded {country}: insufficient data coverage ({coverage:.0%})")

# Create figure
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))

# Create data for the plot
for country in selected_countries:

# Create a visualization showing relationship between economic development and energy intensity
# Get data for latest year
df_latest = df_countries[df_countries['year'] == LATEST_YEAR]

# Calculate GDP per capita
df_latest['gdp_per_capita'] = df_latest['gdp'] / df_latest['population']

# Create figure
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))

# Create scatter plot
scatter = plt.scatter(df_latest['gdp_per_capita'], 
                     df_latest['energy_per_gdp'],
                     s=df_latest['primary_energy_consumption']/50,  # Size based on energy consumption
                     alpha=0.7,
                     c=df_latest['fossil_share_energy'],  # Color based on fossil share
                     cmap='YlOrRd')

# Add labels for key countries
countries_to_label = []
# Top 20 economies
countries_to_label.extend(df_latest.nlargest(20, 'gdp')['country'].tolist())
# Countries with interesting profiles
countries_to_label.extend(['Norway', 'Qatar', 'Kuwait', 'Singapore', 'Sweden', 'Switzerland'])

# Remove duplicates
countries_to_label = list(set(countries_to_label))

for country in countries_to_label:
    country_data = df_latest[df_latest['country'] == country]
    if not country_data.empty:
        x = country_data['gdp_per_capita'].values[0]
        y = country_data['energy_per_gdp'].values[0]
        plt.annotate(country, (x, y), fontsize=9, fontweight='bold',
                    xytext=(5, 5), textcoords='offset points')

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('GDP per Capita (int-$ 2011)', fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Energy Intensity (kWh per $)', fontweight='bold')
plt.title(f'GDP per Capita vs Energy Intensity ({LATEST_YEAR})', 
          fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)

# Add grid
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Use log scale for x-axis due to wide range
plt.xscale('log')

# Calculate and plot trend line (Environmental Kuznets Curve)
# Use non-NaN values only
valid_data = df_latest.dropna(subset=['gdp_per_capita', 'energy_per_gdp'])
x_data = np.log(valid_data['gdp_per_capita'])
y_data = valid_data['energy_per_gdp']

# Try fitting a quadratic curve (polynomial of degree 2)
coeffs = np.polyfit(x_data, y_data, 2)
poly = np.poly1d(coeffs)

# Create x values for the curve
x_range = np.logspace(np.log10(df_latest['gdp_per_capita'].min()), 
                     np.log10(df_latest['gdp_per_capita'].max()), 
                     100)
# Plot the curve
plt.plot(x_range, poly(np.log(x_range)), "--", color='blue', 
         label=f'Trend Line (Environmental Kuznets Curve)')

# Add colorbar
fig, ax = plt.gcf(), plt.gca()  # Get current figure and axes
norm = plt.Normalize(df_latest['fossil_share_energy'].min(), df_latest['fossil_share_energy'].max())
sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap='YlOrRd', norm=norm)
sm.set_array([])
cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, ax=ax)  # Pass the current axes to fix the colorbar issue
cbar.set_label('Fossil Fuel Share (%)', fontweight='bold')

# Add size legend
sizes = [5000, 20000, 40000]  # Energy consumption in TWh
for size in sizes:
    plt.scatter([], [], s=size/50, c='gray', alpha=0.5, label=f'{size} TWh')

          fancybox=True, shadow=True)

# Calculate the change in energy intensity from start to end year
start_year = 2000  # Hardcoded start year
end_year = 2019    # Use the latest year with complete data

# Get countries with data for both years
countries_with_data = []
change_data = []

for country in countries_list:
    start_data = df_countries[(df_countries['country'] == country) & (df_countries['year'] == start_year)]
    end_data = df_countries[(df_countries['country'] == country) & (df_countries['year'] == end_year)]
    
    if not start_data.empty and not end_data.empty:
        if pd.notna(start_data['energy_per_gdp'].values[0]) and pd.notna(end_data['energy_per_gdp'].values[0]):
            start_value = start_data['energy_per_gdp'].values[0]
            end_value = end_data['energy_per_gdp'].values[0]
            percent_change = ((end_value - start_value) / start_value) * 100
            
            countries_with_data.append(country)
            change_data.append({
                'country': country,
                'start_value': start_value,
                'end_value': end_value,
                'percent_change': percent_change,
                'absolute_change': end_value - start_value,
                'gdp': end_data['gdp'].values[0],
                'energy_consumption': end_data['primary_energy_consumption'].values[0]
            })

# Convert to DataFrame
change_df = pd.DataFrame(change_data)

# Sort by percent change (improvement)
improvement_df = change_df.sort_values('percent_change')

# Select top 15 improvers and worst 15 performers
top_improvers = improvement_df.head(15)
worst_performers = improvement_df.tail(15).iloc[::-1]  # Reverse to show worst first

# Create figure
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(14, 12))

# Plot top improvers (negative change means improvement)
bars1 = ax1.barh(top_improvers['country'], top_improvers['percent_change'], color='green')
ax1.set_title(f'Top 15 Countries with Largest Energy Intensity Improvements ({start_year}-{end_year})', 
             fontweight='bold')
ax1.set_xlabel('Percentage Change in Energy Intensity (%)')
ax1.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7, axis='x')
ax1.axvline(x=0, color='black', linestyle='-', linewidth=1)

# Add values to bars
for i, bar in enumerate(bars1):
    value = top_improvers['percent_change'].iloc[i]
    ax1.text(value - 1, i, f"{value:.1f}%", va='center', ha='right', fontweight='bold', color='white')

# Plot worst performers
bars2 = ax2.barh(worst_performers['country'], worst_performers['percent_change'], color='darkred')
ax2.set_title(f'15 Countries with Worst Energy Intensity Change ({start_year}-{end_year})', 
             fontweight='bold')
ax2.set_xlabel('Percentage Change in Energy Intensity (%)')
ax2.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7, axis='x')
ax2.axvline(x=0, color='black', linestyle='-', linewidth=1)

# Add values to bars
for i, bar in enumerate(bars2):
    value = worst_performers['percent_change'].iloc[i]
    ax2.text(value + 1, i, f"{value:.1f}%", va='center', ha='left', fontweight='bold')

# Calculate global average change
global_start = df[df['year'] == start_year]['energy_per_gdp'].mean()
global_end = df[df['year'] == end_year]['energy_per_gdp'].mean()
global_change = ((global_end - global_start) / global_start) * 100

# Add global average line
for ax in [ax1, ax2]:
    ax.axvline(x=global_change, color='blue', linestyle='--', linewidth=2)
    ax.text(global_change, ax.get_ylim()[0] - 0.5, f"Global Avg: {global_change:.1f}%", 
           color='blue', ha='center', fontweight='bold')

plt.tight_layout()

# Add a footnote
plt.figtext(0.5, 0.01, 'Data source: Our World in Data (OWID)', 
           ha='center', fontsize=8, style='italic')
